The spatial deviation between the physical geoid surface and the geometric ellipsoid surface at any given point is termed the geoid height, geoid separation, or geoid undulation.1 Depending on localized gravity anomalies caused by dense subterranean features, mountain ranges, or deep oceanic trenches, the geoid can fluctuate significantly above or below the ellipsoid. Globally, this undulation varies by approximately ![][image1] meters.6

