The ultimate accuracy of any GNSS-derived DEM is fundamentally constrained by the spatial resolution and mathematical fidelity of the underlying geoid model.11 Errors or low resolutions in regional geoid modeling will systematically propagate directly into the calculated orthometric elevations. The International Height Reference System (IHRS) and its realization, the International Height Reference Frame (IHRF), aim to unify these measurements globally, ensuring that neighboring nations do not experience catastrophic elevation discrepancies at their borders.6 Modern geodetic initiatives continuously update vertical datums by combining historic terrestrial triangulation data with modern airborne gravity surveys and satellite gravimetry (such as data from the GRACE mission) to map the geoid with sub-centimeter precision, thereby enhancing the baseline accuracy of all future GNSS topographic workflows.5 Research in the Ulaanbaatar region, for instance, utilized the Digital Finite-element Height Reference Surface (DFHRS) approach alongside vertical deflection measurements captured by digital zenith cameras to refine the local quasi-geoid model, ensuring precise conversion of ellipsoidal coordinates to the Baltic Height system.15

## **The GNSS Error Budget and Atmospheric Signal Distortions**

While the theoretical 3D geometry of GNSS positioning appears computationally straightforward, the physical propagation of radio frequency (RF) signals from satellite orbits approximately 20,200 km above the Earth introduces a complex matrix of signal delays and atmospheric distortions.16 In the context of elevation mapping, vertical accuracy is historically recognized to be 1.5 to 3 times poorer than horizontal accuracy. This degradation occurs due to satellite geometry—receivers can only track satellites located above the horizon, preventing the optimal 360-degree spherical geometric intersection required for perfect 3D trilateration—and because the vertical component is significantly more sensitive to atmospheric delays.18

### **Components of the Unmitigated Error Budget**

The standalone pseudorange error budget for a standard single-frequency GNSS receiver is composed of several discrete contributing factors that must be understood before they can be systematically eliminated.

